Division 3 (rr 25.18–25.24
) also applies in the Dust Diseases Tribunal: see UCPR r 25.1
.

p.text:
The requirement to establish a “prima facie case” is particularly appropriate as a means of emphasising the necessity for a plaintiff to establish the principled basis of its claim: Australian Broadcasting Corporation v Lenah Game Meats Pty Ltd (2001) 208 CLR 199; 185 ALR 1; [2001] HCA 63;  BC200107043 . It is an important consideration where other issues (competing public and private interests) are directly relevant to any assessment of the apparent “sufficiency” of the plaintiff’s claim: Australian Broadcasting Corporation v O’Neill (2006) 227 CLR 57; 229 ALR 457; [2006] HCA 46;  BC200607692 at [65]–[66] . It is also of particular importance in those instances (eg, applications under UCPR 
 rr 25.2–25.7
) where the orders sought are unlikely to materially disadvantage other persons and where the applicant’s entitlement is the principal matter in contention.
